report:
LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  27 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 17-year-old man with a chief complaint of dizziness, lightheadedness, numbness mostly in the arm.  These episodes started over 6 months ago and occur approximately 1-2 times a week.  He has a history of 2 concussions, last 04/11/2013.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Conditions of the Recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well-formed and modulated moderate amplitude 10.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and bursts of theta are captured.
Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort and results in no significant change in the background.
Photic stimulation does not result in occipital driving.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 27-minute EEG. No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinical suspicion for seizures persists, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
__________________________

REASON FOR STUDY:  Differential and classification of seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old male with history of drug abuse, head trauma and a car accident in the 1980's presents to the lab after having seizures since the 1980's, sometimes asleep, described as shaking, also sleep walks.  Last seizure a month ago with loss of consciousness.  The patient is here for differential and classification of seizures in the Epilepsy Monitoring Unit.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote, Topamax and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record appears to have a low amplitude posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is excessive beta seen throughout the recording.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 50-year-old woman with cerebral palsy and mental retardation who presents with episodes of staring, here for evaluation of possible seizures.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient had an increased amount of movement artifact and the impedances were not appropriate for a normal EEG due to the fact that the patient could not be cleaned.  She was agitated when she was being hooked up.  This provides for a very limited interpretation of the EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal and baclofen.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures include photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record appears to have a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta seen.  Overall, the quality of the recording, as mentioned before, is poor and there is a large amount of impedance artifact which prevents any clear definitive statements of abnormalities.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None clearly seen.
SEIZURES:  None.
Please note that at times there were some occipital what appears to be lambda waves but it is unclear if this is a pathologic pattern as this is a poor-quality recording.
IMPRESSION:  Limited EEG which appears to be normal awake.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a limited normal awake EEG.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of loss of consciousness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 20-year-old woman with a history of seizures versus non-epileptic seizures since age 14, is currently 5 months pregnant and is a prisoner.
MEDICATIONS:  Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with and additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and stage 1 sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation and hyperventilation which produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66, however, there appears to be an AV block, although this is only a single electrode EKG.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that a normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Please also note the patient had an abnormal EKG strip which appears to have an AV block, however, a full 12-lead electrocardiogram should be performed and follow up with primary doctor for this abnormality is recommended.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old man with no seizures until 2010.  Now with episodes of shaking without being able to talk lasting a few seconds to 10 minutes.  Denies loss of consciousness but has tongue biting and an aura of rapid tingling in the hands.
MEDICATIONS:  No medications.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening. There is no frontocentral beta. The patient was recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep electroencephalogram.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep electroencephalogram.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of weakness, rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old woman with sudden onset of right arm weakness, lasting 10-60 minutes, then returned to normal strength.  The weakness was associated with tingling and numbness of both hands.  She has a past medical history of hypertension, diabetes, and hyperlipidemia.  Noncompliant with medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Protonix, aspirin, Lovenox, and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Status epilepticus.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old man found down with status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some muscle artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of beta.  The patient is recorded mainly in drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
SEIZURES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The excessive beta noted may be at least in part due to benzodiazepines or barbiturate use.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 43-year-old man who is in prison complaining of left facial twitching for 7 months.  Also reports occipital headaches.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the laboratory using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1-channel EKG and the patient had left facial twitching during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is bilaterally symmetric alpha of 10 Hz frequency which is reactive to eye opening.
Sleep was not achieved during the recording.
Photic stimulation did not elicit any abnormal discharges.
The facial twitching had no EEG correlate.  This is not a seizure.
Heart rate:  80.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake EEG.  The facial twitching had no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Normal EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.  The facial twitching recorded during the EEG was not a seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 43-year-old man with new onset dizziness and drowsiness of 1-month duration, each episode lasting about 1 hour.  This is associated with pressure on the right side of the head.
MEDICATIONS:  Metformin.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement at the bedside and one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a bilaterally symmetric alpha rhythm of 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.
Drowsiness is characterized by increase in beta, attenuation of alpha and some rhythmic central theta.
Photic stimulation did not elicit any abnormalities.
Heart rate 62 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Normal EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman who had an episode of sudden left arm weakness followed by slurred speech.  Lupus, mitral valve disease, multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Plaquenil, insulin, aspirin, others.  __________
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  This is an awake and asleep record.  Technical:  There is a fair amount of muscle artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  The drowsy record is very low voltage with attenuation of the alpha rhythm posts and then lower voltage vertex waves.
Photic stimulation is remarkable for significant muscle artifact, but there is a driving response.
Heart rate 50 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were noted.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 36-year-old man with breakthrough seizures.  He has a history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures and has been off medications for about 2 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel of EKG.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG in maximum wakefulness has an alpha of about 9 Hz, which is of low amplitude.
The patient quickly drifts off into sleep, which is characterized by slowing of the background and vortex phase.
Hyperventilation does not reveal any abnormalities.  The patient becomes drowsy right after hyperventilation.
Heart rate 66 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Left-sided paresthesias.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 62-year-old woman with history of TIA on May 17, 2013, with left-sided numbness and tingling of the face.  Seen here for readmission for the same reason.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, simvastatin, Nexium, clopidogrel, hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril, and oyster shell.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness in stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal and awake sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 31-year-old male who had an episode of shortness of breath, diaphoresis, then slid down on the floor into a fetal position, had an episode of apnea, turned blue and was unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Oxycodone, Xanax, Abilify.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with generous low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta.  Posts were noted in sleep.  The patient transitions in and out of light sleep with scant stage II sleep.
Heart rate 50-60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EKG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  The generous beta may be associated with the use of benzodiazepines.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old gentleman with a seizure 1 year ago.  The patient recalls feeling dizzy, fell down, hit head, and hurt his shoulder.  History of depression and anxiety.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Sleep-deprived EEG was requested but the patient was sent for routine EEG which was performed.  EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  Impedances were left slow almost with the exception of the T1 and T2 electrodes which were 5.6 and 5.7 respectively.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage with a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic central theta.  First excess, K-complex spindles, and posts were identified in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation was performed while the patient was falling asleep and did not otherwise activate the record.  The patient was also falling asleep during photic stimulation without significant driving response.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal low voltage EEG in wakefulness and sleep in an otherwise hypersomnolent patient.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A low voltage EEG is a normal finding.  This patient's excessive drowsiness may be due to the fact that this was a sleep deprived record.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of unresponsiveness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 38-year-old man, found unresponsive and complaining of sharp pain in the right flank and breathing difficulties with agonal breathing into the ED.  He vomited and then had a seizure.  UDS positive for oxycodone, opiates and cannabinoids.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record appears to reveal a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is also reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded mainly in sleep, stage 1 and stage 2.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Please note that the patient does easily drowse off throughout the entirety of the recording.  There is an excessive amount of beta throughout the recording.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Heart rate 100.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG mainly in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal EEG mainly in sleep.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the excessive beta may be due at least in part to medication effects sometimes seen with benzodiazepine or barbiturates.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 27-year-old woman who fell with loss of consciousness on April 17, 2013.  She had foaming of the mouth and said she was having a feeling like she wants to pass out.  While sleeping, she has jerks and sweats.
MEDICATIONS:  Flexeril, Motrin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.  Please note that throughout the recording she has prominent nystagmoid eye movements.
Abnormal discharges:  None.  Please note that she does have some intermittent bursts of diffuse alpha discharge, frequency of bursts seen diffusely, which appear to be most consistent with a burst of drowsiness.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Transient speech changes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of slurred speech and past medical history of multiple vascular risk factors.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, tamoxifen, gabapentin, ramipril.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded mainly in sleep with some wakefulness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens and is mainly in sleep, but the short wakefulness reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Throughout the recording, the patient goes into stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.  Activating procedures are not performed.
Abnormal discharges:  None.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG, mainly asleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal EEG, mainly asleep.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of confusion.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 75-year-old man with complaints of confusion, has had several episodes with a past medical history of hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, Meniere's, GERD, benign prostatic hyperplasia, heart murmur, stroke, and old right intracerebral thalamic stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  Heparin, Protonix, diltiazem, aspirin, Plavix, and trazodone.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures include photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  None; however, there was one sharply contoured transient at F8/T4, seen once during the recording in drowsiness.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  54 and at times appears to be slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges are clearly seen.  There was one sharply contoured transient at the right anterior temporal region, significance of which is unclear.  Prolonged recording with deeper stages of sleep may be helpful or clinical consideration should be applied.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episodes of blacking out.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old woman who presents with a history of blacking out.  She describes this episode as beginning after a fall with injury to a head.  She describes the blacking out events as feeling dizzy, then losing consciousness and being back to baseline after 1 to 3 minutes.  They began in March 2012.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges including hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  Please note photic stimulation produced no photic driving.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
HEART RATE:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy electroencephalogram.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of loss of consciousness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 32 -year-old woman who is 26 weeks pregnant and episode of feeling hot, sating down, loss of consciousness, urinary incontinence, opening eyes with blank stare and no responsiveness.  Back to baseline in less than 1 minutes.  The patient has been nauseous with this pregnancy.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Zofran.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.   Activating procedures included photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  60.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Left-sided weakness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 51-year-old woman with left arm and leg weakness and an episode of left facial droop for 1 minute.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There are multiple artifacts continuing throughout the recording.
MEDICATIONS:  Metformin, amlodipine, Lovenox, Protonix, and hydralazine.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 11 Hz, however, is seen with a high amplitude over the right side compared to the left.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation which produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  90.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  21 minutes.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old woman with a history of migraines for the last 4 to 5 months associated with left facial twisting when the headaches occur.  This lasts only seconds but facial tingling and pain lasts for several days thereafter.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include tramadol, __________, Tylenol with codeine.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well formed and modulated low to moderate amplitude 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving with multiple flash frequencies.  A regular heart rate is captured on a single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
No stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake only 21 minute electroencephalogram.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine electroencephalogram does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Nearly 21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 53-year-old man who had a single convulsion on 01/28/2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Not known.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Both hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes are captured.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort and results in no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  EKG artifact is noted throughout the recording.
FINDINGS:
Stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 21-minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 24 -year-old woman who has a history of seizure onset at 13 days old following meningitis.  Seizures are described as twitching of the left side of the face with associated tongue biting. These episodes last approximately 5 to 10 minutes.  Last such event occurred in approximately 2004/ 2005.
MEDICATIONS:  Currently Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low amplitude well-formed 10 to 10.5 alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening. There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness, POSTS (positive occipital sharp transients in sleep) and symmetrical vertex waves are captured.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces mild diffuse background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 24 minutes EEG.   The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
__________________________

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  26 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 49-year-old man with a history of hepatitis C, polysubstance abuse, seizures, and depression who had questionable seizure-like activity while in a CAT scan.  Six mg of Ativan was subsequently given.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan 6 mg and Dilaudid 1 mg during the EEG.  Percocet, Keppra, Advair, nicotine patch, morphine, Protonix, and insulin.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with the addition of T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated low to moderate amplitude 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are observed.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  Early in the recording there is a significant EMG artifact due to the patient locking his jaw.  Additionally, an episode of rapid generalized shaking is captured.  This episode lasted approximately 20 to 30 seconds.  Electrographically, it is associated with diffuse pronounced EMG artifact without associated ictal activity prior, during or after the episode.
FINDINGS:
Episode of shaking without  abnormal ictal activity.
No epileptiform discharges.
Stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 26 minute EEG.  An episode of generalized shaking was not associated with abnormal ictal activity captured on scalp EEG.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 33-year-old man with history of seizures and a motor vehicle accident in 1997.  Last seizure was in April 11, 2013 with generalized tonic-clonic shaking, loss of consciousness, fall and confusion.  He has a history of schizophrenia and bipolar disease.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Neurontin, Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and stage 1 and stage 2.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient recorded during wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE:  96.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.  No seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 51-year-old, right-handed gentleman, with history of headache and seizures who presents for followup EEG.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 10 Hz in frequency, 10-30 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is diffuse low amplitude beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact as well.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response. IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording, capturing wakefulness through drowsiness.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are a clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.  Generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepine, barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

The patient is stimulated during the recording and there appears to be some muscle artifact and mild reactivity to the EEG.  Overall, the background consists of delta, low amplitude delta slow waves with intermittent bursts of theta and some focal slowing which are described beyond normal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal slow waves seen intermittently over the right hemisphere, maximal at C4/T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20 microvolts.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz, amplitude 20 microvolts, occurring continuously with intermixed theta slowing seen infrequently.  Again, there is some reactivity to this EEG.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing, as well as some right central temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right centrotemporal region which is consistent with a known tumor.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology, but may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through stage 2 sleep.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old male with epilepsy since 2006.  Nocturnal seizures, the most recent one week ago out of sleep with incontinence and postictal confusion.

There is also some rhythmic central theta, and in sleep electrode artifact was observed at T4.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for artifact and scant, supra-harmonic driving.
Hyperventilation did not significantly activate the record.
In the transition to drowsiness, there was a single, subtle left temporal transient.
Heart rate 72 bpm.  Rare PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging, but normal EEG in wakefulness and brief sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No definitive epileptiform features were noted.  There was a single, subtle, left temporal sharp wave.  In that there is only 1 sharp wave, this must be considered artifact.  A repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep may be of value to more definitively characterize this patient's epileptiform activity.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was a routine 22 minutes EEG with acceptable impedances.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  Other features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.
Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal features were identified.  This EEG will be used for this patient's surgical baseline.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 38-year-old with epilepsy, seizure free, until a seizure several weeks ago with shaking headache.  In addition aura  of visual scintillations.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  This is a routine EEG with acceptable impedances.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a low voltage, 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta.  The patient quickly transitions into stage 1 and stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation was deferred.
Heart rate 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The patient appears to be quite sleepy.  Photic stimulation was not performed and if a generalized mechanism for epilepsy is important, a repeat study should be obtained.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 24-year-old woman, 20 weeks pregnant, with an episode of loss of consciousness for 10-12 minutes and an inability to speak with associated dizziness.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were deferred. This Is an awake and asleep record. It Is technically satisfactory, although there were some problems with the
T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz., 40 microvolt alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with POSTS and vertex waves noted in stage I sleep. Vertex waves and spindles are noted in stage II sleep.
Heart rate90 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were Identified in this record. If epilepsy is an Important consideration, a follow up, more prolonged EEG may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 28-yea -old woman with numbness of the right face and head, lasting for 2-3 days. Symptoms occurred 1 week ago and previously 2 years ago. Evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is a technically acceptable EEG aside from the T1-2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with an increase In beta and then rare vertex waves and K complexes.
Photic stimulation elicited vigorous bilateral driving. Hyperventilation produced bursts of relatively synchronous bilateral slowing.
Heart rate 66 bpm. slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness and early sleep.
CLINICAL No focal or epileptiform features were identified in the record. If epilepsy is an Important consideration, a follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 68-year-old woman with syncope and a fall. The patient recalls having chest pain. Flushing and palpitations and then became amnestic.
MEDICATIONS: Losartan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake an asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta. There 1s intermittent, temporal theta noted in relaxed wakefulness. Hyperventilation produced scant bilateral theta. This is followed by a drowsy pattern with attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicited brief bilateral driving.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were noted in this record. An adult of this age is permitted a small amount of temporal theta as described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old woman with restless legs syndrome and epilepsy, as well as generalized anxiety disorder.  Currently, seizure-free for 2 years but has a feeling as if her left leg is moving, as if there is something inside of her leg, associated with leg pain.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zoloft, Requip, insulin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This is a technically satisfactory, routine, greater than 20 minute EEG with photic stimulation.  This is a primarily awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with a patient who appears anxious with frequent muscle movement.  A 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm was identified.  Abundant lambda was noted.
Photic stimulation elicited vigorous bilateral driving.  Heart rate 110 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG primarily in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The vigorous driving described above was noted in the 2006 EEG.  This is the 2nd, normal EEG for this adult.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 21-year-old female with multiple concussions, most recently October 6, with headaches and intermittent difficulty with concentration.
MEDICATIONS:  Elavil, albuterol, Naprosyn.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.  It is technically satisfactory with impedances under 5 kilohms.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Alpha squeak was noted.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta, but sleep was not sustained.
Hyperventilation produced a small increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate: 55 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  In this individual with a history of head trauma there was no background slowing noted.
